      <mj-section>
        <mj-column>
          <mj-text padding-top="0">
            <p>If you would like us to include your entry in the newsletter, please <a href="mailto:info@borehamwoodshul.org">email</a> the office.</p>
            <p>Please remember to update the Shul office at your earliest convenience if any of your details need changing.</p>
            <p><strong>If you or someone you know is unwell</strong>, please let one of the Rabbinic Team know or contact Karen on <a href="tel:07341005116">07341 005 116</a> or email <a href="mailto:care@borehamwoodshul.org">care@borehamwoodshul.org</a>. We are here to support you in times of need.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-spacer height="10px" />
        </mj-column>
      </mj-section>
      <mj-section>
        <mj-column>
          <mj-text mj-class="section_header">
            <h3>
              <!-- Dash &#8209; -->
              <!-- htmlmin:ignore --><a name="dt"></a><!-- htmlmin:ignore -->D'var Torah by Rabbi Alex Chapper
            </h3>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text>
            <p> We’re understandably shocked, but not surprised, by Wednesday’s terrorist attack in Golders Green. Another week, another act intended to spread fear and intimidation within the Jewish community. Our first thoughts and prayers are with the victims, their families, and all those affected.</p>
            <p> While those who sponsor and perpetrate these antisemitic attacks are driven by hatred and evil, the Torah issues a majestic call to us: to make a Kiddush Hashem - to sanctify G&#8209;d’s Name. This isn’t an abstract or elusive ideal, but a deeply practical mandate to bring holiness into the fabric of everyday life. But how do we achieve it?</p>
            <p> By remaining true to our mission. By acting with kindness, dignity, and integrity. By cherishing the gift of life and living it with purpose.</p>
            <p> The Rambam teaches that when we live in a way that reflects the values of Torah, it inspires others to recognise something greater beyond the individual - a life guided by G&#8209;d. In this sense, every one of us becomes an ambassador of G&#8209;d in this world.</p>
            <p> That’s why we’ll never run or hide from those who seek to harm us, because making a Kiddush Hashem demands something more. It calls on us to live with pride in our identity, to stand firm in the face of hatred, and to respond to darkness not with fear, but with light.</p>
            <p> That is our strength. And that is our message. </p>
          </mj-text>
        </mj-column>
      </mj-section>
