      <mj-section>
        <mj-column>
          <mj-text>
            <p class="title">Yahrzeit Information</p>
            <p>You are kindly reminded that if you are commemorating a Yahrzeit and would like your loved one's name to be read out in the Memorial Prayer, or if you would like a Mitzvah in Shul on the preceding Shabbat, it is essential to return the form on the bottom of the Yahrzeit notification by post or <a href="mailto:yahrzeit@borehamwoodshul.org">email</a> by the previous Thursday at the latest. Otherwise, it may not be possible to offer you a Mitzvah on Shabbat morning.</p>
            <p>You can also contact the office via phone on <a href="tel:02083865227">020 8386 5227</a> or <a href="mailto:yahrzeit@borehamwoodshul.org">email</a>, to request that your loved one's name be included in the Memorial Prayer with the Rabbi.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text mj-class="section_header">
            <h3>
              <!-- htmlmin:ignore --><a name="crp"></a><!-- htmlmin:ignore -->CRP - Certificate of Religious Practice
            </h3>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text>
            <p class="title"><strong>Collection of CRP points to start school in September 2027 has started.</strong></p>
            <p>You must register each child you plan to collect CRP points via synagogue attendance here: <a href="https://myus.theus.org.uk/crp-application/crp-user-login/">myus.theus.org.uk/crp-application/crp-user-login/</a></p>
            <p>The dates eligible for CRP collection are between <strong>18th April 2026</strong>&nbsp;and <strong>9th January 2027</strong>&nbsp;(but please check with the school you are applying to as deadlines differ), both BES@Croxdale &amp; BES@Yavneh will be using the United Synagogue system,&nbsp;<strong>if you plan to attend both sites, you will need to register separately for each</strong>.</p>
            <p><strong>CRP Desk</strong></p>
            <p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The CRP desk is where the sheets are handed out to those arriving to record CRP attendance. We rely on volunteers to run the desk, so please help if you can. If no one volunteers, there will be no CRP desk that day. <strong><a href="https://borehamwoodshul.org/crp-desk-sign-up">Please sign up here.</a></strong></span></p>
            <p>FAQ’s and more information on CRP can be found here: <a href="https://www.theus.org.uk/crp">www.theus.org.uk/crp</a> or contact <a href="mailto:crp@borehamwoodshul.org">crp@borehamwoodshul.org</a></p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text mj-class="section_header">
            <h3>
              <!-- htmlmin:ignore --><a name="other"></a><!-- htmlmin:ignore -->Other Information
            </h3>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text>
            <p class="title">Cholim &amp; Refuah Shleima</p>
            <p>If you know of anyone who is unwell in whatever way, please email their Hebrew name (with their mother's name if known) to <a href="mailto:info@borehamwoodshul.org">info@borehamwoodshul.org</a>. Names on the list will be read in Shul on Shabbat with a new list being generated once a fortnight. To all our members or their family who are ill, in hospital or recuperating from illness or surgery, we wish them a Refuah Shleimah. Also, please let Karen or one of the Rabbinic Team know. They are here to support you in times of need.</p>
            <p class="title">Women's Mikveh</p>
            <p>Please text or call <a href="tel:07504 927 066">07504 927 066</a> for appointments - please try and give at least 48 hours notice. For Friday night or Yom Tov please contact Rebbetzin Chapper on <a href="tel:07850036046">07850 036 046</a>.</p>
            <p>The refurbished Keilim Mikveh is also available at Croxdale Road.</p>
            <p class="title"><a href="https://bes-website.s3.amazonaws.com/web-images/legacy.png?mtime=20231107172246&focal=none"><img src="https://bes-website.s3.amazonaws.com/web-images/legacy.png?mtime=20231107172246&focal=none" width="180" style="float:right;margin:0 0 20px 20px;" /></a>Leaving a Gift in Your Will</p>
            <p>The United Synagogue powers Jewish life through its 56 communities and the critical infrastructure and programmes it provides for the British Jewish community.</p>
            <p> At a time of such uncertainty and worry, the importance of standing strong as a community is even greater – as is ensuring that these values are passed down to those who come after us.</p>
            <p> By leaving a gift in your will to your US shul you will enable your community to thrive and ensure that it is there for the next generation.</p>
            <p>For more information contact Elliot Shorrick: <a href="mailto:eshorrick@theus.org.uk">eshorrick@theus.org.uk</a> 020 4529 9792.</p>
            <p class="title">Safeguarding Information</p>
            <p>The United Synagogue is ever more conscious of the threat to children and vulnerable adults from people who would seek to do them harm - whether by physical, emotional or sexual abuse or by neglect. Within every United Synagogue community therefore there is a volunteer Community Safeguarding Coordinator (CSC). This is someone within the community who is the primary point of contact at local level for members of the shul if they have any concerns in relation to child protection or the protection of vulnerable adults.</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong class="croxdale">Croxdale's</strong> Community Safeguarding Coordinator is <strong>Katie Matlin</strong></li>
              <li><strong class="yavneh">Yavneh's</strong> Community Safeguarding Coordinator is <strong>Helene Silverstone</strong></li>
            </ul>
            <p>They are the grassroots point of contact for our community and will pass on any concerns to and receive advice from the United Synagogue Head Office Safeguarding Team.</p>
            <p>If you have a concern and would prefer to speak to someone within the United Synagogue Head Office Safeguarding team, you can reach them on <a href="tel:02037588440">020 3758 8440</a>. You can use this number for any safeguarding concerns either current or historic. If ever you believe someone to be at serious imminent risk, you MUST call 999.</p>
            <p>-</p>
            <p class="title">It's wonderful to see so many children and young people joining us on Shabbat. To ensure everyone feels safe and welcome on our sites, we ask that all children and young people under the age of 18 attending Croxdale or Yavneh be accompanied by a parent, a responsible adult, a trusted older sibling or a family friend aged 18 or over.</p>
            <p> We understand that parents and guardians are not always able to attend themselves, but we ask that you ensure any child or young person coming to our sites does so with appropriate arrangements in place. As the signs on our premises make clear, Borehamwood & Elstree Synagogue is not responsible for the supervision of children on site, and that responsibility remains with parents and guardians at all times - whether or not they are present.</p>
            <p><em> If you have any concerns about behaviour on site, please raise them with an Honorary Officer, who can be identified by their badge. For safeguarding concerns, details of the safeguarding coordinator at each site are clearly displayed on the premises.</em></p>
          </mj-text>
        </mj-column>
      </mj-section>
      <mj-section>
        <mj-column>
          <mj-text mj-class="section_header">
            <h3>We wish you Shabbat Shalom from the BES Team</h3>
          </mj-text>
        </mj-column>
      </mj-section>
